I really recommend getting Kovaak if you enjoy playing FPS games. The game itself won't improve your actual aim much, but I feel like it makes it easier to. Play it for 20 or 30 minutes before starting your desired FPS game, and you'll notice how much more consistent your aim feels. Don't be discouraged, as the hitboxes can feel unforgiving in comparison to any FPS game that isn't CSGO, where even the hitboxes aren't hitboxes, but don't let the frustration get to you. There's are a wide variety of minigames to help you improve in your desired category, and if you don't feel like crafting a routine by picking a bunch out from the vaguely named online scenarios, there is an extensive KovaaK's workout guide you can find on Google (it's a dropbox file).

Some people disparage aim training and its effectiveness in games. If you are one of these people I say this with the most respect, you are misinformed and are making a philosophical and psychological mistake. Aim training is nothing more than improving mouse control and reactivity to a moving or stationary target. Some of the best players in each on of their respective gene of first and third person shooters, have done some kind of aim training/mechanics isolation before in their careers. Weather that is this program (Psalm 2nd in the Fortnite world cup, Daquan[The most entertaining Fortnite streamer I have had the pleasure to watch], Beaulo [Prefessional Rainbow Six Siege player for TSM at the time of this review]), a healthy variety of different types of programs (Shroud, Myth, Booty clap KC) or has played custom games with bots for hours upon hours a day with the intent to improve (Nate Gibson) we all have the drive to improve ourselves and be better then we were yesterday. Maybe this will be the final leap to making you a professional/semi-professional player in your game of choice. I will achieve that level one day and I know you can to, these people I mentioned did it so why can't you? There is no excuse for not wanting to improve and become a better version of yourself even if you do not want to be a professional player. If you have come from console (like me) I would strongly recommend consulting Aimer7's guides on aiming, this includes the positioning on as well, for the people with many years of First person shooter experience you can most definitely improve on you game sense. These are the guides and there respective links:Aimer7 Workout Routines (I would recommend doing the complete routine for console players):https://www.dropbox.com/s/vaba3potfhf9jy1/KovaaK%20aim%20workout%20routines.pdf?dl=0Aimer7 Positioning Guide (Even console players can benefit from this):https://www.dropbox.com/s/aif0jy1prxe0rjm/Heuristic%20about%20geometric%20positioning.pdf?dl=0One more thing before you start your improvement journey, diet, physical exercise, and proper sleep have huge effects on how well you will be able to aim. I have personally noticed an increase in reaction time from 180ms average to 150 average on human benchmark:https://humanbenchmark.com/ by focusing HEAVILY on improving my Daily routine/Eating habits. I would also recommend the content on these youtubers:Blink: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCzn7P3lnglgxwHM_kFQ0AOARon Rambo Kim: https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCr97_mhDwscRciN6eWyXLowNow a wildcard interview from a professional Rainbow Six Siege player, this has sparked my interest in reaction time and nootropics: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ui898Biq_S4I am by no means a professional in any of these topics and I am constantly learning about the world of E-sports/improvement. Right now I am a advanced beginner according to Aimer7s guide, and can 100% attest to the effectiveness of this guide. I hope these tools give you the motivation to continue to push forward and accomplish your highest aspirations in life. Much love to all of you and God bless. <3

Kovaaks is great for training your muscle memory in regards to the movements associated with aiming such as flicking and tracking (mouse control, hand-eye coordination, and speed specifically). I think the worse your aim is the more you stand to gain from using Kovaaks to take your game to the next level. However, it's not some magic panacea where after a month of grinding a playlist or two you'll become an aimgod like Shroud or KennyS. (They are the exception and have hundreds of thousands of hours playing FPS' titles for years even before mainstream aim trainers have even existed)


You have to be consistent with your training regimen and keep at it, similar to people trying to get in shape by using the gym. Hoping for overnight success without putting in the work will only leave you jaded and disappointed. As an aside I'd recommend making sure you spend plenty of time in your target game while using Kovaaks since aiming is only one part of becoming good at an FPS title where game/map knowledge, decision making, movement, positioning, teamwork/communication (If it's a team-based game), and recoil control are just as important as bettering your aim (Things you can only really practice by playing your game of choice). If you have realistic expectations, set some tangible goals, stay committed, you'll be surprised how much you can improve at your target game. Also make sure that accuracy is your #1 priority, speed will come with time.


I've only been using Kovaaks for a little while now but I've started to notice that my flicking and tracking have incrementally gotten better resulting in winning more gunfights, but I still have a long way to go to be more competitive in the games I play. Bottom line is what you get out of Kovaaks is what you put in, it's a tool, but an amazing one for the FPS enthusiast that takes it seriously.

Im just gonna say kovaaks is good but i hate the ui / ux, the aim training tho is very very good i just cant stand the ui. kovaaks vs a aim trainer like aim labs
kovaaks - more options for training more styles of aiming (shows you your high score and you get your score for the task you just did vs your high score)
aim lab - good for basic aim training but you wont be able to get as much variation on aim practice (gives you more specific things about your aiming issues + score and high score)

both programs are good but if you want to actually see progress you want to practice every day for a minimum of 1 hour (best to do this before you go to sleep because your muscle memory will get finished learning faster when you sleep)

if you choose kovaaks look into aimer7's aim guide for kovaaks, if you follow you will have a much better time learning / improving aim.

You want to train your aim? Then this is the "game" for you.

Personally, I think it is best to practice one aspect for a set period of time like 5 days and set a goal that you want to reach by then for example:
I want to improve my tracking accuracy from 42 -> 50%. 
Play f.ex. Ascended Tracking v3 for 20 min a day then play challenge and write down you results WITH THE DATE in a textdocument. This will motivate you because you will see how much you have improved.

Here are my favorite maps for the different aim "aspects"

Tracking:
Ascended Tracking v3
Popcorn Goated Tracking(Hard)
Cata IC Fast Strafes
mccoyfrozentrack (tracking taping accuracy)

Flicking:
The build in "Trainer" feature (I think asp is a great weapon of choice for this)
Jumbo Tile Frenzy, Tile Frenzy or Tile Frenzy Mini
Reflex Flick - Fair
1wall6targets TE

ACCURACY:
Valorant Small Flicks (Flicking and close accuracy)
Valorant One Taps

The base game, the sandbox mode, works great. No doubt about that but the added Trainer and it's algorithm as well as the provided user experience need a lot of work.

To the developer:
- Consider the option for people to skip a level. Sure, there is the aspect of earning it, but the algorithm totally ruins every bit of progress if you have one bad run. It feels like it doesn't take it's own issues into account. E.g. if you spawn 30 targets on the left and you miss the 7 of 10 targets that spawn on the right, of course the percentage of the targets you miss on the right is higher, but you have no chance of correction in that case. Writing "please excuse any odd data in the software" is not the correct way of handling things. Either you give the user the option to skip a stage when the algorithm does not perform as intended or you just don't release it in the first place
- Following situation occurs too often and should be taken out. You play one level and finish it BUT you have to play it multiple times afterwards to prove that you finished it and not just by chance? I get the point but from a usability and reliability perspective it makes no sense to implement since it is a frustration factor for the user. Imagine you finish the level twice well and don't perform as good to any factors that YOU AS THE DEVELOPER can not change, user error. What you do is make the user repeat everything from the start, there is no reward in doing that but only frustration.

What I mentioned above is the reason I won't recommend this software, no matter how far the development is, until the usability and reliability of the "software and odd data" is not conflicting.

EDIT:[b] Just get Aim Lab.[/b] It's free and actually on track to being a well polished aim trainer. 

tl;dr They need to fix crashing and UI. And, to justify the price, should include more game support out of the box (even if they are stripped down). There is a just a huge lack of features, and compared to other free options

Date: July 10, 2020

[b]Positives:[/b]
[list]
[*] [strike]Cool tracking and training in "Training" mode[/strike]
[*] [strike]Seems robust and ambitious with its training features[/strike]
[*] I guess there's a community
[/list]

[b]Negatives:[/b]
[list]
[*] Should be labeled Early Access
[*] Barely any loading bars/signs/etc to let you know the game isn't frozen
[*] Hanging loading screens (looks like it froze)
[*] CRASHING on loading screens (like I can't play 3 rounds in a row kind of crashing)
[*] No data tracking in the classic mode (just high score)
[*] Very few games supported in either mode
[*] ONLY Overwatch and Fortnite supported in the "training" mode
[*] Horrendous UI
[/list]



If you get passed crashing at launch, the first thing you'll notice is the horrible wall-of-text UI. You'll try some "sandbox" and find out it does not record any of your data but a high score (so no record of how much you've improved over time). Additionally, the settings do not include many common popular FPS games. 

You figure you'll try the actual "Trainer", which will give you analyzable data but will only allow you to select from Fortnite and Overwatch...the games that are, unless you go pro, some of the least aim heavy on the market. Also, not as popular as they once were. So I have no clue why these were chosen for the new mode. And, after a round or two, will crash with no error message or notice of any kind.

Everything about this screams early beta. And, with free options on the market, it's hard to justify paying for this. Extremely disappointed.

Out of all other aim trainers I've seen or tried out on the Internet, this one works. Kovaaks is a really efficient way of practicing point-and-click mechanics that apply to most modern FPS titles and it is great for players that are moving to PC gaming from console. Be careful how you use the program though. Always focus on improving yourself and don't get heavily emotionally invested into your scores or leaderboard ranks. Look up some good scenarios to play, try them, and if you like them, create your own practice playlist and run through it every single day for at least 45 minutes. I promise. This game is so worth it and your aim will definitely improve. Many other professional FPS coaches would probably agree with me and I've heard many players who've tried Kovaaks and they say it is the best thing to use to practice their aim. If you are new to PC FPS gaming and are looking for a good, reliable aim trainer to practice on, Kovaaks is for you.

Alright, listen here. I have over 2000 hours on CSGO, and the countless hours on Half Life & CS 1.6 LAN Multiplayer with my friends at the internet cafe back in the days where we played with a roller ball mice. 

And one thing I've learned in all these FPS games, they are all aim, track, and click games. 
Of course, in general they're much broader than that. 
But in the end, 98% of the time you'll die because your opponent aim and click at you. 

And KovaaK provide you a platform where you can improve your accuracy, tracking, and reaction time. So? Will it make you a better FPS player? Yes. of course it will. 
But GAMESENSE wise, you'll need to play your FPS game of choice with real people in order to gain it, in which I think is just as important as your accuracy. 
It doesn't work if you have one but not the other. You gotta make it 50/50. 
And KovaaK is here to give you a chance to improve one of your 50.

There's a ton of aim trainers out there, they are all pretty similar, to be honest.  I think the main thing that jumps out about KovaaK is the community created drills.  Other than that, there's tons of options to match your sensitivity for your preferred game, hit sounds, weapon sounds, etc. are all tweakable to your liking.  Another thing is the ability to have the leaderboard default to a friends only view so if you like to compare to your steam friends, that's useful.
So many scenarios that are constantly updated makes this a great aim trainer that can really be tuned for whatever fps game you want to get better at.

EDIT: This program FALSELY ADVERTISED. Read further to see why.The program weighs far too lop-sided. I've had most of my runs, where 55% of my missed shots were on the right or left side, fully inconsistantly. Randomly. Not because I couldn't hit on that side, but because random targets happened to surprise me there that time. If you accept the adjustments, the program throws MORE bots to the left, which means, if you flick with the exact same accuracy, just by statistics, you're gonna miss more on the weighed side. I know myself, that I can't shoot for sht on my lower right, because the gun model blocks my entire view there, but the program has no ability to notice that, therefore I could never practice that specific angle. Also, when the program doesn't find any mistakes, it makes ones up randomly. I did control-groups, where I didn't flick at all, and slowly moved my cursor over to the exact same amount of targets on each side in the quadrant-controll exercise. The exact same hit locations on for dummies, and every shot not taken after those. The program concluded, that my lower left quadrant was weak, and would procede to give me 3 train-levels of lower left, in NEITHER can you level up. Do I have to browse through the workshop for that? Also, the program's screenshots include hanzo's bow from overwatch, but that mode is not available, or at least locked behind some unexplained requirements. If it is, how does it make sense to complete however-many hitscan levels, to be able to go to tracking? And there are a TON of hitscan levels. Do you have to become a GOD Widowmaker, before you can practice hanzo? Is this some sort of gatekeeping? In it's current state, the program is not polished enough to be worth its price, that is my opinion.
Edit: this genious program reset my 5 hours of progress I had in it. https://imgur.com/a/s8u1vbh if you don't believe me. My highscores are still there, but I have to re-do the entire program again. Now that I play it again, and have SO MUCH BETTER results, the program still looks down on me as if I was just lucky, and makes me re-do the stages. It just doesn't let me through the 4-directional flicks. I am sure that there is a programming issue with the stage, as the developers don't seem go have any sense for statistics, and will just randomly go out on tangents about random one-click mistakes. Oh, you couldn't get a single target on the right side? Must be because that mistake is DEEPLY ROOTED IN YOUR SYSTEM, AND WE MUST ERADICATE IT! Now DO IT AGAIN like a good little btch! The visuals are ugly, the program looks like one of those 'I made the mirror's edge running animation in unity in 24 hours' videos, and most of the job, and anything that's actually useful, like tracking and scoping, is done by the workshop. This is nothing more, than an overgloryfied shooting gallery, and SHOULD BE FREE. Or at the very least optional to pay, or free with microtransactions (skins on the dummies, for example), because dummies randomly spawning in unity engine, grounded on the foundations of simple-as-nail if/else commands is not what I was promised. You are paying 10 euros for community made maps basically. That's literally the only thing this shooting gallery has that others don't, and I am very disappointed in my purchase. No, flipping a coin on my better than avarage results if I can  maybe get to see further levels is not what I was promised. I did not want to pay 10 euros for a skybox and seemingly free assets popping up that I have to click on, and a single menu, with absolutely no freedom given to the user to gauge his/her abilities or decide for themselves which level is best suited for them. This is a hoax at worst, and you can get the very same skills and results with any free alternatives. It just sounds good, when someone like xQc says the words "aim trainer" in a video. Reality is often disappointing. Verdict: will this improve your aim? Yes. Is it worth your money? Not at all, not even at half price. Go download something for free, because mechanically you're gonna get the very same improvement. Go spend that 10 euros on dinner, instead of supporting this horrendously lazy developer.

They will soon stop surprising me and make these kills second nature. Kovaak will have most to do with that. The times I die because I whiffed my aim is reducing and I die mostly in most situations because the enemy is just plain better than me.

Firstly, the email harvesting is intrusive and annoying. I don't want something like that from a simple aim trainer that I've already bought through Steam. Being forced to login again is a pointless nuisance. Clearly, the only reason this retrograde feature exists is to harvest emails for bonus profit. Just charge more for the game! If it's actually worth it, people will pay. But they know it's not worth it.

A lot is made of how the features hidden behind the registration and login allow you to train with something close to a real-game setup. This is just marketing nonsense. It doesn't.

To find out that the new training is bad, means you've already had to register, and they've got your email. Being exploited like that is not endearing.


And what is does after you register definitely isn't worth it.

The "new" training experience is disappointing. The long, unnecessary delays where it pretends to be downloading data (what data?) analysing your data (what, forty clicks?) just get in the way of practice. It would take less than a millisecond to calculate a hit/miss ratio, or per quadrant, or whatever. Not that it will even tell me my per-quadrant ratio...

In practice, the statistics are amateurish and lacking completeness or utility. For example, you will get something like this:

"55% of your missed targets are on your left. Your left accuracy needs improvement."
Firstly, 5% deviation there probably isn't meaningful. If I missed 70% of targets to the left, maybe it would be important, but 5% is well within a margin of error. If you accept the questionable suggestion to put more targets on left, it will then (and this is bad statistics management from the trainer) complain that 90% of your missed targets are on your left... Of course they are, it put 90% of the targets on the left, so of course that's where the misses are; you have almost no chance to miss on the other side.

That is takes so long to produce such a broken analysis, and makes such ill-founded recommendations is the main reason for my bad review.

There are other problems along this line.

For example, it never complains about top screen/bottom screen accuracy, even though for me, this is more pronounced.

It doesn't distinguish near misses from complete misses, or have any statistical measure of accuracy other than simplistic hit/miss. Now, in a game, only hits count, but for training, the other data does mean something.

Nor does it consider the distribution of targets. It doesn't take into account the real difficulty of a shot, given sequential placement of targets. Instead, the targets are completely random, and it provides no data about sequential tracking. So when it puts five targets in almost exactly the same spot on the top left, then one on the far bottom right, hidden under the character's arm, it considers that bottom-right shot to be just as easy as the ones that were all in the same place and clearly visible.

Also, every session, I find my mouse creeping down and down the desk towards me until I run out of space. This is a non-problem in a real game, it's only a problem in the trainer. The sessions should have mouse-reset pauses, where it stops for a moment. This would allow for longer sessions, with better average data. The current sessions are quite short. You should at least have options to configure this sort of thing.

Overall, I find the long "analysing" delays between sessions extremely frustrating, and doubly so because the authors don't seem to grasp even basic statistics. I'm not even sure they understand anything about mouse movement difficulty and how it impacts real shots.

Even if the analysis code were written in Python, or R, it would still be effectively instant for the tiny number of data points it handles. So what is the program doing during those long, frustrating delays? I don't think it's doing anything, it just puts in the delays to try and con you that it's doing something clever.

And the lack of configuration options for how things are measured is apparent. You can't choose between square quadrants and radial quadrants for example. It seems the program is using a square quadrant model, which is inherently flawed.

But... It's the delays that make this an unendurable experience. Why are there analysis delays? Why are there loading delays? Loading delays on a 32GB PC, to show a level that consists of nothing but a low resolution model and a background image! This is just ludicrous.

The sound is unpleasant, from the robot voices to the cold, repetitive music. I don't need a music track from a game like this, any time or effort spent on it is wasted. Doubly so if it's so unpleasant to listen to.

Some basic features are missing too. You can't turn off the stupid screen-covering arm. You can't customise your cross-hair. It will let you play flicking training using a machine gun, which produces garbage results ... and so on.

There is no customisation of the guided training mode at all. Again, a big oversight. If I could do things like set up "head shot only" mode with a distribution for flick distance right from the start, that would let me address something I want to train, instead of what it thinks I should do.

You have to log out to swap back to the classic mode, which is hardly an intuitive way to integrate it.

The "classic" mode, or whatever they call it, is better in many ways. It's what you got in a lot of other trainers. But it's just the same, there's no reason to buy this over those other trainers except for the new mode, and the new mode is not well done.


Then there's the video support...

I have an ultra-wide monitor, and true Fullscreen mode won't let me set the ratio I want to fill, instead trying to occupy all of my 32:9  5120x1440 screen (impractical, and looks bad because it doesn't even suggest the right resolution).

Windowed mode FAILS TO CAPTURE THE MOUSE properly, causing the program to be unusable... Fortunately, Fullscreen-Windowed works sensibly, but only one out of three modes usable? That's not good.

Some other programs have similar problems, but well made ones do not (Overwatch itself is fine for example).


Finally, the graphics are "programmer art" and look quite bad. They do not create a professional or polished appearance. I could forgive that if other aspects were right, but they aren't.


There are some reasonable ideas here, but the execution is flawed and incomplete. It calls the analysis "beta". I wouldn't describe it as even reaching an alpha standard, and it's not even in a program being sold as incomplete.

Long delays, pointless registration, that I don't want ... it's clearly to scrape extra monetization off customers who already paid ... plain bad statistics ... and a extremely limited configuration and customisation options.

While other trainers also have weak statistics, they cost less, load faster, have no pointless forced delays, offer more customisation, and their training modes are ultimately just as useful, and perhaps more realistic. And they don't harvest your email address or force you to login.

This offers no benefits over other trainers, costs more, and harvests your email.

My suggestions is to avoid it and buy a different trainer.

Before buying you should know that improving ur aim require consistency in your training schedule , you should put 1 to 2 hours in it everyday and play the good scenarios for what u want to improve. there's alot of routines available , best free one is probably Aimer7 one. if you want to improve more and really strive to be the best aimer possible , you should consider getting custom routines and coaching with vF or sparky coaches.


so to resume:
- be consistent , don't miss a day in the schedule because of lazyness. you can take breaks from time to time if you have pain to avoid injuries or if your mental is not in a good shape.
-play good scenarios. don't spend your time playing tile frenzy or things like that , most of the good scenarios have moving or small targets , or both.
-be patient , you may not see great improvement in term of scores on the scenarios as fast as you expect. but if your more comfortable with your mouse and develop a better mouse control , results are gonna show in the FPS you play and slowly scores in kovaak will grow

Essential for any serious FPS player. Many ask "Why not aim train in your chosen game?" While aim training within your chosen game is also beneficial, few - if any - games actually offer you the opportunity to, 

1.Isolate your exact weaknesses effectively, [b]without[/b] down time. The down time is a huge one for BRs.
2.Control the exact scenario(s) in which you are practicing, and when you practice them.
3.Practice situations which are mechanically [i]much[/i] more challenging than situations found in a match. "He who can do more can do less" (Aimer7). That is to say that practicing scenarios that are way harder than in-game ones will make the in-game scenarios that much easier.

I had more reasons but I can't think straight. Here's [url=https://www.dropbox.com/s/vaba3potfhf9jy1/KovaaK%20aim%20workout%20routines.pdf?dl=0.]
Aimer7's training guide. [/url] Just as essential as the tool itself.

A lot of people say that aim trainers are gimmicky -- and those people are right.

Aim trainers are a great tool for improvement, but they're just that: a tool. They only work if you use them in addition to other games to train your aim. You need to play a variety of scenarios in order to practice aiming in different ways. Too many people make the mistake of sitting in KovaaK's or Aimlab all day and never hopping into a game to practice. If you only play an aim trainer, you'll just improve at the aim trainer. 

That said, when used properly, a game like KovaaK's will help you make rapid improvements. It's sort of like working out: you keep getting gains, but with diminishing returns, and you have to keep at it. If you want to add an aim trainer into your daily regiment, KovaaK's is the best in the business.

The "Trainer" is a set of developer created scenarios for the user with special features released with version 2.0. The "Sandbox" has user created scenarios and was there from the start.


The majority of my hours are from when the game was at version 1.0. The game was a lot more lightweight then and it didn't have an unnecessary "Trainer" along with it. Before this addition, the game was less than a GB, roughly 700 MB. Now it is about 8 GB. For an aim trainer, it should be as lightweight as possible while maintaining features that the users want. Now more about the "Trainer". This in my perspective is aimed towards the people who are attracted to aim trainers like "Aim Hero" or "Aim Lab". They're appealing to people who haven't educated themselves about what their best options are or people who want everything pathed out for them. While that it is nice that developers would try to make it easier for the user to get started, it is not an effective way to train aim. Before the 2.0 update with the "Trainer", the "Sandbox" was and still is the only reason to purchase the game. The majority of people that bought the game prior to 2.0 were made aware by it from streamers where they played a couple of scenarios like Tile Frenzy and Ascended Tracking. Now I am assuming it is the "Trainer" luring in new users which I also assume was their plan in creating it. The reception the developer team got from the community on the release of 2.0 was anything but positive. Look at the negative reviews in the community hub or the subreddit if you want to know how bad it was. 


I got about 100 less FPS with the release of 2.0, I brought it up in the Discord server and did not receive a response. They never addressed the performance degradation from my knowledge. There have been issues with AMD drivers and this game, requiring AMD to fix their drivers. They recently added analytics that from my knowledge you can only opt-out by sending a letter? I would recommend reading their privacy policy https://themeta.com/privacy-policy. The "Trainer" requires an internet connection to play but the "Sandbox" does not. I thought their UI rework would make the UI look a little better but it still looks outdated and made by a developer and not a graphics designer. 


The Meta is what the developer team for "The Trainer" call themselves, a team that was working on their own training platform before merging with Kovaak's FPS Aim Trainer. Subsequently after that merge is when this game started going downhill with the addition of "The Trainer". Quote from the TechCrunch article: "After the two esports entrepreneurial teams met, they decided to join forces and offer what they believe to be the ultimate training tool." The team has also raised some money "The gaming startup has raised $2.5 million in funding from investors". I can only speculate to the reason for why Kovaak decided to merge his game with something comparatively inferior. 


While Kovaak's FPS Aim Trainer still maintains "The Sandbox", the addition of "The Trainer" and The Meta team has really made it something I would stay away from. Turning from a friendly developer into a corporation asking me to accept a 3rd party EULA.  Aimbeast seems closer to what Kovaak's FPS Aim Trainer was like around 1.0 and I would only really recommend an aim trainer to somebody inexperienced with FPS games.

I thought I had decent aim but i felt it was lacking at times so I decided to try kovaak's. At first I was disappointed at how simple the top rated games were and I was skeptical that it would translate into other games. On top of that the challenges felt very taxing on my brain and I would get burnt out after 20 minutes. The median scores were surprisingly high and seemed out of reach. However I kept playing for 20 minutes a day during my down time and within a week the challenges were no longer exhausting me mentally and became very fun. I found myself playing kovaak's over my other fps games, trying to top my high scores and climb the leaderboards became very addictive, especially coupled with the fact that I knew I was becoming a better gamer in the process. Now after just 3 weeks of playing I consistantly score in the top 80-90%. I've noticed a huge impact in other fps games; I get compliments on my aim from spectating teamates regularly now. This game also was immensely helpful in finding my optimal DPI and sens, which i was way off from and had no clue.

This game has made my other shooter games more fun as I'm better at them now. This is possibly the best $10 I've ever spent on a game.

TLDR;
- Skeptical at first
- huge improvement very quickly
- definite translation into other games
- helped me find optimal DPI/sens which i was way off from and didn't know it

It's probably the best aim trainer out there just because of the community integration and the variability in training exercises that allows for. Additionally, the recently added ability to make playlists for exercises is brilliant, it can be buggy at times but that feature alone is a game changer. Anyway here's my nitpicks:

-There's no "reset to default" for the graphical options, actually a really big annoyance for me.
-There's some pretty bad lag upon initially starting the game due to it having to load all the workshop maps, I'd like it if it only loaded those when you opened the workshop browser, that way I don't have to wait 30-60 seconds (on SSD) before starting a 5 min warm up exercise that I have saved.
-To add to the above issue, It isn't uncommon for the game to be unresponsive on startup, forcing you to ctrl+alt+del out of the game and deal with the load time again.
-There appears to be a little bit of lag when initially starting a challenge, can be a little frustrating to beef 2 seconds into a 1 min challenge just because of some slight lag. This seems to have been improved in updates but still exists.

Again these are all pretty nit picky, just mentioning them because it is such a simple game designed to do one thing really well, which for the most part it does. I'd definitely buy it on sale, but I'd never buy any aim trainer off sale, either way this is the one to get at the time of writing this review.

Provides a wealth of aim training scenarios for you to practice both core and fringe components of FPS aiming and allows to you see how you compare with other users. The sandbox is probably where you'll spend a lot of your time exploring scenarios and warming up. 

The guided training is still in progress but could use a lot of work. Some of my major complaints:
- There seems to be some sort of disparity in the tracking. I have no mouse acceleration turned on and I checked Windows, my mouse driver, and Kovaacs itself. Yet while practicing flicking, my mouse is consistently drifting towards me. Unlocking vertical and horizontal sens and instead setting them to the same amount seems to help. I'm using an ultrawide monitor, which may play into this. Either way, it's an issue they need to fix.

- For a guided training, it does not provide very useful information with regards to what you need to do to move on. Sometimes in flicking, it tells you that high accuracy is more important, other times it tells you that speed is more important than accuracy. At the end of each trial, it gives you very limited information about your performance and nothing about what your score made you fail that level. It's kind of frustrating. Yeah if I had 100% accuracy and lightning quick aim, I could definitely move on, but I don't, which is why I'm going through this training in the first place. 

Don't expect much from the training mode. It only has 1 out of 3 modes available right now anyways. For now, I would stick to the user-generated scenarios as your mainstays. It probably doesn't provide anything that Aimlab doesn't, though, and Aimlab is free, so...

[h1] HONEST REVIEW (LONG) [/h1]
[b] Summary [/b]: KovaaK is a great tool to help improve your aim (and some movement if you play Quake, I guess), but it's still up to you. You won't be a God just by training KovaaK, you still have to put in the time in whatever game(s) you play.

This aim trainer will definitely help you, [b]provided you use it properly[/b]. I'm saying you should work on what you're lacking on. Of course, it depends on which game you play, and your play style. I play CS: GO (1.8k hours) and Apex Legends a lot, so I adjust my training for both games accordingly.

[list]
[*]In CS you utilize more flicking and shooting heads over tracking, so I focus on 1wall 6targets and other flicking/target switching challenges, and add some Cata IC to brush up on tracking. The Short Strafes version is extremely helpful in CS, as a lot of high-level players with great movement tend to sidestep a lot.
[*]In Apex, tracking is a lot more prominent, so I tend to utilize more Ascended Tracking, Cata IC, Vertical Tracking, and such. 1wall 6targets pasu is surprisingly hard and should help you switch targets while also tracking them. This is very useful in Apex, as everyone is running around all the time.
[/list]

Even only after less than 15 hours put in, I've seen a major upgrade in consistency, and adjusting to targets is much easier. 100% recommend this aim trainer. Definitely look into AIMER7's guide, you can look it up on Google. The guide will help you set up nicely.

Use KovaaK responsibly. Again, this and only this will not make you a God. The time you put in, in whatever game you play, along with proper KovaaK training, will definitely enhance your mechanical skills and push them to the next level. Can this make you as good as Shroud/Aceu?  [spoiler] Yes. It definitely can. [/spoiler]

I think it's a good idea for an aim trainer but, the "trainer" portion needs some serious work. There's clearly something wrong on a basic level. I will complete a training session and it will tell me that "55% of misses were on the left" then it will say it's adding more targets on whatever side it thinks you need training on. This sounds good in theory but, that seems to be as far as they got in that algorithm. Now with more targets on your weak side you of course have more chances to miss on that side but, it doesn't seem to account for the extra targets. Other times it will just switch what it thinks you need work on based on who knows what. Sometimes it won't even tell me a percentage of misses and instead will just say "Most of your misses were in the bottom right". There isn't really any progression because as soon as you think you're making it somewhere everything changes.

There's still other things in the general sandbox that I think are more like the original Kovaaks. This game really needs to add in some other settings for other games so you don't have to figure out the sensitivity on your own. I don't play fortnite or overwatch and that's all that's avaulable in trainer. 

tl:dr there's plenty of free trainers out there that with help you with a flick shot or tracking. This one has a long way to go before it lives up to the hype of the first one

I have no idea what's going on. I saw videos of the original Kovaak and thought that's what I was getting; a simple, clean, easy to use trainer with no frills. I get into this and am immediately bombarded with confusion. Why is there a robot? Why am I getting options to play with Overwatch weapons? Why do I need to register? No way I'm registering for this... I just want to practice my aim! I don't want to go online!

So I figured maybe "Trainer" was the wrong mode and went to Sandbox instead. I have a list of 5 recommended scenarios, so I figured I'd try those out... but I can't even figure out how to do that. Why do I randomly have like 16 local scenarios already and why are half of them starred and half not? Why are there weird player names on my screen called "A_frozen_pistol" and "react"? Am I online or something?! What's a session manager? What's the difference between "Start Challenge" and "Play"? And "Start Playlist"? I tried going to "Online Scenarios" and figured out you can click this tiny little "play" button next to the name, so I clicked that... and then proceeded to wait 5 minutes while it says it's downloading scenarios. What? Are you trying to download EVERY online scenario or something? Just let me play!! 

So finally I tried making a playlist. I figured out how to add stuff to it. But when I try clicking "Play"... nothing happens... I can't double-click the scenarios to play them... the play buttons next to the titles don't do anything... I'm completely lost on how anyone can use this.

Anyway, I have no idea what's happening. Half an hour later, I haven't even been able to do something as simple as make a playlist. This may be some of the worst UI design and user feedback I've seen in any game, period. I'm disappointed, because the program I saw online looked really good and clean. Currently trying to find any way I can of getting the old version... what a headache...

review: Great way to practice your aim throughout different scenarios. I'm new to mouse and keyboard so I have a pretty early starting point in terms of when I began using this in relation to my start. It has helped tremendously for some situations such as strafing but I have concerns it could hamper my aim If I were to simply go for high scores. This is due many scenarios that don't give you a chance to reset your arm. It's also a fun way to kill time while trying to relax. The only real con is being forced to send usage stats and the inability to disable this "feature".  All things considered there really isn't too much to consider, kovaaks is far and away the best aiming simulator currently, outside of ethical issues. I can't recommend a game that needlessly forces users to send data to the developers. I should be able to opt out, period.
developer_response:
A little more context about our data collection:

The analytics calls will be made when gameplay isn't going on (after challenge ends, or otherwise while paused).  The data that will be sent is all stuff like "user went to this section of the UI" "challenge named <> started" "challenge named <> completed".  The EULA will have info on opting out.  

ó €€The reason behind analytics is we want to figure out where users are spending their time (keep in mind Steam has their own analytics on stuff like Workshop scenario usage, but we can't actually see any of that ourselves despite being the devs) and use that knowledge to guide our development.  It's all of the sake of making the best product we can.

review:
9.5/10 The best aim-trainer I've tried, period! 

PROS: There are so many different scenarios and practices to do. Having a challenge mode with leaderboards makes it easy to track your progress and see how you fare among others as well as giving you that competitive drive to keep grinding at it and improving. I think KAT is 100% definitely worth the cost even when it's full price, but if you can get it on sale then it's even better. After a few weeks of playing KAT almost daily for 1-2hrs a day, I can say with certainty that my aim has improved drastically. Seeing your high scores increase in scenarios is 1 way to track your progress, but I think an even better way is just feeling the difference in your game of choice. In a lot of situations where I probably would have choked and not hit a single shot under pressure, I can now easily just react to being put under pressure and my muscle memory does most of the work for me. There are so many selections of great scenarios people have created, many of them really help you identify where your weak points are with your aim.

CON: the only negative I can really find with this aim trainer is that there aren't options for custom crosshairs. There are quite a few options with your choice of custom colours, but some of the crosshairs provided are really out there and ridiculous, ones that nobody would ever really use in any tactical fps game. I really wish there was a custom crosshair section, something like in Overwatch with multiple sliders that let you fine-tune how thick or long the lines are, if you want an outline or not, or if you want a dot and how big that is, opacity etc.. If it had that then I'd give it a straight 10/10, but not having a crosshair option like the ones I use in game is a bit of a bummer. I like there to be a small gap in my crosshair for me to lineup headshots with, but the crosshairs similar to that in Kovaak's either have to large of a gap or no gap or a gap so small you can't really get an idea of what's in the center of it.

 Overall thought, I would HIGHLY suggest this aim trainer and also following a guide so you know you're doing scenarios that are the best for you, AIMER7 has a great thorough guide that I tell everyone I know to follow as a guideline if you don't know exactly where your aim needs work: https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=1351275779

Then at the end of the retry, you have to press next and then play to retry the map again which is a really small thing, but it lacks the non-stop feel that I think a playlist should have.

Other than that, a fantastic practice tool, thanks for the continued development

It's a good aim training tool, offering several different training scenarios for you to practice. Disclaimer that I've only used Kovaak's sandbox, so keep that in mind as you read my review.

I think the sheer number of scenarios you can try in Kovaak's matches or exceeds that of any competitor, which might make the price worth it compared to other free aim trainers for some people. On top of that, there's many different pre-made aim training guides which are tailored around Kovaak's, so getting started with a strict routine for improvement is easy. 

Having the leaderboards for each scenario is useful for benchmarking your performance with a specific routine and giving you a sense of which areas to work on the most. Though I don't believe the Kovaak's sandbox itself has any sort of in-game analytics or performance-tracking, the game can be set up to export cvs for each challenge completed for each scenario, and the community has created an online dashboard which visualizes your progress over time using those csv files ("FPS Aim Trainer Dashboard").

One criticism I have is that in my experience, the game menus in sandbox are somewhat slow, unresponsive, and prone to freezing. Within the scenarios themselves, I have never noticed any issues with performance (no frame dropping, for example), but for example, searching for a specific scenario using the search function in sandbox takes longer than you would think, and clearing the search doesn't work with the "x" button either. Loading the game directly into sandbox also requires me to load into at least one other scenario before I can do anything. 

These kind of performance issues in sandbox definitely remind me that I paid money for the game (considering there are free alternatives), and it could be a complete turn-off for some people. However, my overall experience with the game as an aim trainer is positive, so I would recommend it (maybe avoid paying full price though).

===  1 WEEK UPDATE  ===

After using Kovaak's aim trainer consistently every day for a week, I can say that I have experienced a noticeable increase in my in-game performance. I have more confidence in my aim, so even whiffing a few shots doesn't instantly tilt me anymore, and I noticed a massive increase in the number of headshots I land since I started training. 

Because I am seeing the results of Kovaak's paying off in-game after only one week, I would definitely recommend this game to someone who is willing to commit to a daily routine even at full price. 

However, if you're just curious in seeing how an aim trainer might work for you, I think it would be better to try one of the free trainers and see how you feel before pulling out your wallet for this one.

No aim down sight, no recoil, no scopes ? For an FPS trainer you'd expect at least these features, come on now.

The whole thing just screams "half assed". 

There are some major oversights that just seem unprofessional. For instance, if you're often missing the targets that pop up on your right, the game will add more target on the right so that you can train yourself. Now that could be a good idea except that the dumbass who made this game doesn't account for the skewed proportions when it'll calculate the balancing next round. So first round it spawns 50-50 on your right/left, maybe you miss more on the right, maybe you miss more on the left. Balancing happens. Next round it spawns 70% to your right because that's the ones you missed. Question, when there's more targets on the right, guess which targets you're more likely to miss? Enter: the vicious cycle. Now it's 10-90. Then it's 1-99. Wow! The only targets you missed were on the right this round! Jee, let's add more!

I mean christ, if you managed to fuck *that* up I wonder what the rest of the game will be like. I got a refund :I

[h1]8.5/10 Effective but not entirely intuitive at first glance.[/h1]
In detail; Kovaak's allows, for the measly price of $10 USD, any person to train for any fps currently available in a way similar to how a gym works. By creating practice scenarios that only focus on one skill such Flicking and Tracking, or more specific scenario-based skills such as hitting with slower moving projectiles and quickly moving from target to target while scoped in. In 2.0 there's a directed training mode that, even though the game has a focus on Underwatch and 2 weeks, teaches you important skills that can be used in nearly any fps. While the Directed Training Mode is much more intuitive and even learns where you need help, it doesn't truly help you with game specific situations. But that's where the sandbox mode comes and the game's biggest issue also comes into play. The sandbox training mode has you download scenarios from the workshop. Most of the ones out there may not give you the training you need or they may be above your skill level in the first place, or may be for an entirely different game. Sadly, the way the workshop content is handled in the sandbox is perhaps too bare-bones and requires you to just kinda figure it out to find out what scenario works for you. Thankfully, the community content is focused and at the time of writing none of the scenarios are actually impossible nor are they far too easy to get any kind of meaningful learning from. With time, more people will create more content for more games and hopefully the workshop scenarios will be able to supplement the directed training. Overall, a great training tool that will only grow in value and currently worth the price as it stands while writing this review (4/25/20)

The best aim training product I have ever used. At first it seemed daunting, but after playing for 10 or 15 hours, I began to notice that my aim felt more "snappy" and I didn't have to make such large corrections when popping to targets. After a hundred hours, I honestly feel like my aim is better than most people in FPS games. Sure, I still get killed and lose plenty often, but that's usually because I put myself into dumb situations, not because my aim failed me. Sure, this game will not help you with "game sense," but it will help you get on, and stay on, target faster and more efficiently. I highly recommend this to anyone serious about improving their FPS gaming.

This aim trainer helps improve hand-eye coordination, reaction, mouse control, and aim overall (like tracking and flicks). There are a ton of maps for different games, and different aim training. You can control how many bots there are, and what type they are. I recommend the Ascended Tracking map, which helps tracking, Tile Frenzy which helps micro flicks and medium sized flicks, and Snake Tiles. Snake Tiles has 25 tiles that you have to move your mouse onto, and is great for switching targets quickly. Kovaak 2.0 is a great game to practice aim and reactions. It can help in any game that involves aim.

These guys have truly thought of everything!

This "game" is semi helpful. Even though it is not finished it has only been a let down. There are only 2 games to choose from to get practice for. Fortnight and Overwatch are both popular games but not necessarily needing to train for. More first person shooters would be better. Examples are Rainbow 6 Siege, Call of Duty games, and many other normal gun usage games. Fortnight is stuck in 3rd person mode all the time so if you wanna work on that you can. Overwatch uses random weapons that are main for its game. Another down fall of this is you can only work on "Flick" training for now. To be honest tracking and scoping are more important than flicking. Flicking requires speed over accuracy and if you are using this for other shooters you need accuracy. I have worked on the flick training and honestly not reliable. It takes to much work to move up and many of my shots were on point but didn't connect. The game also has a sandbox mode where you are able to kinda train on other things, but only shows shot hits and a K/D ratio. This game/ trainer needs significant updates and work done to make it better. Until then I would not recommend this to any first person shooter players.

Awesome Aim trainer only 2 days in and I feel that I have already improved my aim.

Honestly, THIS is it. This is the game you need to play if you want your aim to be better. With community made maps for a variety of games and aim styles, from tacking to flicking, it has it all, projectile, hit scan, lasers, everything. The built in trainer, although being new- is extremely well made and can tell when you have inconsistencies that jeopardize your aim, like missing a lot of left shots, It'll spawn more targets to the left so you can improve your aim. It has an AI that learns off of your shots landed and missed, very similar to a school course, it has multiple different nodes with different practices to improve flicking skill. What more can you ask for.

-Second time i launched it had resolution issues with mouse cursor clicking in the wrong position.
-Couldn't hide the weapon despite marking the option for it.
-Not a lot of graphical options compared to the first version.
-You are required to register and rewrite your login information every time you launch.
I'd say that for 10 dollars, you can see improvement in any aspect of your aim, as long as you're consistent, and  keep a routine going.

People say ''their is no shortcut to get good a gaming'', but this is the closest you can get.

10/10

KovaaK has a lot of neat and fun workshop challenges/scenarios to help improve your raw aim. Will it help you win or get a better K/D in your favorite games? Not exactly. You will still need to improve upon other vital skills  that you can only learn by playing more. While fun, this should be used more as a tool to tinker and build consistency with your mouse settings/set-up.

Quality of the product aside for a moment, the devs are pretty amazing. I had technical problem that rendered the game unable to load properly. I emailed their a supported, explaining the issue. Within a week, they resolved it for me. I'd happily buy this game 5x over with this kind of support. 

Now onto the quality of the product: it's good. Very good. You have to find the scenarios and routines that work for you. But the game is amazing at giving you a quiet spot where you can just hammer away at the mechanical aspects of your game. I' have 100 hours in and I've really seen an improvement the games I play. That said, you gotta mix in both. Do a training session for 30 minutes, then hop into your game of choice to reinforce the training. Rinse, repeat.

The analytics are pretty much useless. It just shows you a target with hit markers as to where you hit it. Telling me if I missed to the left or right doesn't tell me if I over aimed or underaimed because they spawn on both sides.

Great for practice in any type of shooter game. If you keep at it, you will most likely see great results. It has a trainer and sandbox mode. While the trainer mode is kind of okay, it gets annoying when it tries to adjust to help you and adjusts too much. Most people recommend the sandbox mode where it lets you play maps made by other people, there are more than 3,000 scenarios made to help you at almost anything.

As it currently stands I would not recommend this version of Kovaak. Mechanically it's great but the feedback system is incredibly unhelpful with no clear goal of what needs to be achieved during training. Users are forced to grind and grind and grind with recommendations that really don't make a difference. Unless dramatic upgrades are made I will be requesting a full refund.

My verdict? "Partial Pass Condition".

This trainer has so much potential, but it's SO frustrating and at times buggy.

Sometimes you'll get stuck with long pauses or blank screens.

The trainer will tell you that speed is more important than accuracy, and then on the exact same page also tell you that accuracy is more important than speed (before giving you a game where speed is the only option because the target life is so short anyway).

Robot gibs will inexplicably fly towards you, obscuring your sight lines and breaking your concentration.

And most frustratingly, it'll leave you stuck on the same level for dozens and dozens and dozens of attempts, and no matter how well you think you did, it'll fail you ("partial pass") without actually telling you WHY it failed you. Then it'll say you did great and you'll probably pass "soon", before going on to fail you a few more dozen times for no clear reason.

It took me a matter of minutes to get to level 2.3 and then I've been stuck there for hour after hour after hour of play time (currently >15hrs) invested over multiple days, with zero sense of progress and no idea why it won't let me continue. There's only so many times you can be told to replay the same level for no apparent reason before you start wanting to throw something out the window.

It's so nearly what it deserves to be, but it desperately needs more work on the reward schedule in the trainer (and an editable FOV there too) before it deserves a recommendation.

I'm average at most FPS games. Every once in a while I'll get a good streak and carry my team, but every once in a while I'll go an entire match without killing somebody. I figured an aim trainer would be perfect just to get me above average.

So this has game has two basic options for training. Overwatch and Fortnite. I was really wanting to practice soldier from TF2, but that's not an option. They showed it in the advertisement, but it's not actually a possibility.

This game has two games inside of it. Trainer and Sandbox. But the engines between Trainer and Sandbox are literally two different engines. So you'll take a ton of time to configure you're settings to the way you like it, switch to the other mode, and none of it matters. They don't even have an option to save a configuration to each mode.

I can't even get my native resolution to work in "Trainer" mode, so it defaults to 1920. But then I come back into sandbox, and my screen is stretched out!

I really think this is a great idea, but this needs some work. I feel like it's way to inconsistent to measure trainable precision.

https://github.com/SteamRE/DepotDownloader/releases
(if program does not run - you need to install .netCore from https://dotnet.microsoft.com/download



Now back to the review.

Beware of the new "Train" mode. It's a bold statement from developers to claim that their training routines will help you. Expect wave of negative reviews after months with comment that Train mode has ruined aim of those players.

For example from my experience with other aim trainer - training routine "flickshot as many big targets as possible in a given time" had really bad affect on me, because I have started to subconsciously panicshooting into general direction of enemy (to at least try to randomly hit them in a given short time) instead of giving them a solid headshot. As soon as I have noticed this new patter in my aiming style - I have switched to different training mode with as small targets as possible, to train precision instead of speed. And my result in the games has improved since then.
I can already say this game's first row of flicking train routines will have a bad result on me. Been there, done that.

Don't get me wrong, it is of course great that they provide list of training routines and progression, and etc. It is fun to challenge yourself and complete them. But right now they will force teach you some bad habits. This kind of coaching should be done under supervision of trained professional, and not by some scripted game.

Another point - aim precision extremely depends on FOV (view angle in game). I can't even change it in the game int the Train mode. I don't even know what is default fov in Train mode. And what if I play different game with different fov? Noone should train on this game's default fov and then try to go back to his favorite game with different fov and expect improvements, result may be even worse after that.


tl;dr: developers have no idea about human physiology related to aiming. They will ruin your aim skills if you will blindly trust them and train according to their list.
There are a lot of things to consider about aim training. Players should not think about that, this has to be considered and done by "aim trainer" developers. But developers don't do that in this trainer.

Just use the old sandbox mode and enjoy nice workshop maps.
developer_response:
Thanks for taking the time to leave a review. 

We donâ€™t pretend to have all the answers as there is no surefire â€œone size fits allâ€ solution for improvement. What works for you might not work for someone else. We have done more than a bit of research into training fine motor skills and decided to test the speed-accuracy tradeoff hypothesis that training speed over accuracy at the outset results in performance gains. This proved out well in our alpha testing last summer, as our players saw significant improvement. 

With more data from more players, we should be able to effectively tune this and hopefully optimize the experience for more players. 

So, we consider the trainer to be part of the process, not the whole thing. Which is why we suggest and link to Sandbox scenarios for players to practice once they unlock them in the Sandbox. 

That said, we deeply value your opinion and know that, together, we can build the best trainer for the most gamers!

I don't usually post reviews but I feel I need to for this.

After using Kovaak for only 4 hours I have noticed a drastic improvement for my aim on CS:GO and I do think it's a good 'game'.

So why am I not recommending it? I wish I could have a neural response to add to it and my main reasons are that this is solely community driven. I personally wouldn't play it and I believe the majority of players wouldn't play it if it wasn't so community driven. You could argue that they still built the base mechanics but even that is something that can be done with little knowledge of game design and done in an hour or two tops.

All this to say, I think it should be free, since it's a community driven game. I do think there's going to be something better coming along that holds the same principles but adds more elements such as playing alongside your friend in a similar fashion to Osu!. 

TL;DR Will help you improve but it should be free

I genuinely believe this might be the fastest way to get comfortable with a mouse & key gaming experience for players who are new to PC. I struggled pretty badly with getting used to M&K on multiple games, and opted to use a controller whenever possible so I'd at least be able to participate (Apex Legends, mostly).
After about my 20th hour of Kovaak, my aim is way, way better than it used to be. I'm not close to perfect, but at least I can compete now with M&K. 

I do remember the first ~5 hours were very stressful, knowing how awful I was compared to everyone else on the leaderboard (I scored dead last on one of them). Now I'm above the Median on most things I try, and that feels good.

This will make you a better PC player, especially if you're new to M&K.

I recently took down my review of KovaaK 2.0 as there has been major changes to fulfil community requests

After the most recent update it seems that the aim trainer now has TWO major sections, Sandbox and Trainer.

Sandbox-
probably the most attractive part about this, and what all older players are use to. you can download custom maps from the community workshop to train in your own way and style, there is also a challenge mode where you have 1 minute to try and score as many points as possible. 

Trainer-
something new i found to be interesting, its like a workout routine where after you improve you progress to a harder and more difficult level, there is currently 1 game mode, flicking. however 2 more are supposedly coming, tracking and scope. it seems that this game mode is only for overwatch and fortnite as those are the only 2 games available. however it seems it doesn't matter. it also seems to be very detailed as the targets aren't spheres or squares, but actual player models

FINAL VERDICT
this is currently the best aim trainer on the market, most people flocked to this in 1.0 which has now become the sandbox mode, this should be your MAIN reason to purchase this game as it is super simple and effective. trainer seems to be very promising in the future and if you don't feel like you are improving because of sandbox, give trainer a try.

I played this game a whole lot and it really helped me with getting better at aiming, which has been my greatest challenge in fps games. This most recent update, though, has completely ruined the game for me. The appeal of the game was the absolute 100% customizability and simplicity of it. You could train whatever part of your aim for whatever game you wanted (vertical aim, tracking, flicking, etc. etc. etc.). The new update destroyed that positive about the game. Now, when you launch it, you have to agree to a third party EULA AND provide your blizzard or Epic Games account in order to even use the game (even if you don't play ANY games from blizzard or epic)... Even after maneuvering the new, confusing ui, and getting to the main game that people bought (and not some random crappy fortnite simulator), you will see that all of your settings have been reset and the gun model has become about twice the size, blindingly white, and super distracting, along with everything on your screen becoming blurry as hell. Refund us, or separate this new shitty update into a seperate game, and let the actual users of your product use the product they bought.

I just played the re-release of the 2.0 update.

I didn't play the first release, but from what I just played, it looks extremely promising. I am loving the flicking stages, and like how it starts easy and slowly gets more challenging. In between stages, there's a recommended sandbox scenario to practice on, which I've been using because it's a focused training level for flicking. I'm assuming these kinds of recommended scenarios will also be added for the tracking and scoping modes

After the stages, the reviews of where your shots landed are super helpful so you know what direction to improve in. You're even given the option to spawn more targets in whichever direction your aim is weak in

I can't wait for the Tracking stages to be added - flicking and tracking are pretty much the most important skills in any shooter, and this update is really quite amazing imo

First legitimate review + some advice, sorry if a bit all over the place.

I spent approximately a rounded 200 whopping hours grinding my aim in KovaaK's FPS Aim Trainer and I definitely noticed improvements more so specifically in my mouse control and the appearance of my aim also looked smoother across the board as my friends began noticing and would compliment my aim fairly often.

If you're looking to zone out to The Glitch Mob's Drink the Sea album and not think for several hours and aim at a hitbox, then the game is great... but if you're trying to legitimately improve your aim and dm than I highly suggest avoiding aim trainers because the artificial scenario training system that aim trainers provides more often than not builds bad habits and doesn't always provide the same 'aim under pressure' scenarios that actual gameplay provides. You tend to also develop tunnel vision and suffer from usual aimer symptoms that I noticed after more than half a dozen years of competing in various FPS games with aim-heavy players (i.e standing still, holding W, not being able to comm on your microphone and play at the same time, etc.).

Tl;dr - A lot of the features that KovaaK's provides CAN legitimately improve your aim and mouse control, but what is actually going to get you to where you want to be is focusing on your dm in actual scenarios in your games rather than relying on this artificial gameplay.

Something else I noticed about the game and more so specifically the Discord servers and Steam groups formed from the game are pretty reminiscent to MENSA in my opinion, where many of the players grind scenarios for scores rather than to build on their aim and many of the players who grind to place high on the leaderboards only really do so  to gain "popularity points" or even sometimes the social benefits in the Discord itself which I feel distracts players from legitimately seeking to improve.

I can't believe I put 87 hours into an aim trainer already. But after 800hrs of pubg and 800hrs of Apex Legends I couldn't even break a 1.0KD in Apex. At 36 I'm a pretty below average FPS player but I was sick of getting beaten down and figured I'd check out this app I'd heard so much about. I'm so glad I did, I was concerned that the scenarios in game wouldn't translate to the FPS games I play and at first it really didn't. It's a bit overwhelming with hundreds of scenarios that are attempting to teach multiple different aiming techniques and styles.

I stuck with it though and it really wasn't until I found Sparky's Benchmarks and Aimer7's guide that things took off. These gave me something to strive for and really opened my eyes to how much I well... sucked. So I started playing their recommended scenarios, just trying to beat my personal records and get somewhere close to their benchmarks. I'm finally seeing tangible results! I've seen my KD increase in every FPS I play. In Apex it nearly tripled. I've noticed things about my mouse control and my mental approach to aiming that I hadn't even thought of before. The differences between arm aim vs wrist vs hybrid. How you shoot a fast strafing, close up target, how to deal with multiple targets at a distance... you can basically find weaknesses you have, then use the Kovaak's scenarios to grind that exact scenario over and over until it becomes natural, ever tried vertical tracking? Yeah me neither, at least not explicitly; it's a lot harder than I thought.

It's so much more satisfying playing competitive shooters when you actually ARE competitive. I feel like Kovaak's has given me the tools to improve my game with it's hundreds of scenarios and customization options. I practice 15-30m a day sometimes more depending, it's fun and really satisfying trying to break your records and seeing yourself improve. I know a lot of pro's talk shit about Kovaak's but for us plebs that weren't born with pinpoint aim and the movement of a gazelle, this is a great way to git gud.

This game changed my FPS level immensely. I used to be what I thought was decent at shooters, and after following the training regimen that is provided in the Kovaaks subreddit for about 3 months I have become huge amounts better at every FPS game I play. I recommend finding your mouse sensitivity and maintaining the same sens across all games - for me I lowered my sens to 750 dpi and 8 Overwatch/BNET sens (23.091 cm/360). You can use a calculator online to see what sens this is for other titles. Follow a routine for one hour a day at least 5 days a week to improve your tracking as well as reactions and you will see insane improvements. Honestly I can't thank this game enough.

I no longer follow the training program and my level remains the same  (no improvements though). I don't play as seriously as I used to so this is fine with me. But if I ever wanted to get serious again - Kovaaks will be  the place to go.

I had been using KovaaK as a warm up and training tool for my FPS skills. I was really enjoying it as it was simple to use, and had a tonne of variety available due to the user content. Unfortunately, when I attempted to do the routine I was working on, I notched that the game had now changed drastically and was called KovaaK 2.0: The Meta, and was taken over by a completely new dev team (also called The Meta) and they've ruined what was once a simple and great tool to facilitate improvement.

Now once you login to Steam and click on the game, you need to login or register either an Epic or a Battlenet account so you can play this new game where they "guide" your development in either Fortnite or Overwatch, and for this privilege, you have to agree for The Meta permission to sell your personal information. To add insult to injury, the performance of sandbox mode, which is essentially what the game used to be, is now horrific, to the point that it is (at time of writing this) damn near unplayable.

I can't in good faith recommend this game in it's current (2.0) state, and the direction it is now taking under new leadership, is no longer a game I would ever want to play.

The Meta update is a step towards attracting more audience to the game with more guided features and feedback systems, it's totally understandable. But the core audience of Kovaak's that grinds this game everyday already has a good idea of what they need, they just want a simple aim trainer that works and Kovaak's did just that.

 For someone who wants to grind a game to get better at aim, consistency is important. That's why the new update is pissing people off, it's not improving upon what's always been there, but adding new things that core audience don't want to cater the new players.

 The amount of aim trainers out there are increasing, and the number of people who's willing to grind trainer everyday is not a lot, most people try it and quit.  kovaak's had a healthy amount of dedicated audience and now it's sacrificing the quality of life of them to attract the new players, who, for the majority won't play this game for more than 1 hour.

 With that being said, with the new update, the sandbox mode is the same as old Kovaak's, the lighting is atrocious though, if they fix that, I can deal with it. Or just freaking give me my baby back. It was my one and one true love and now you took her away...
