[u]About my aim history: [/u] All my life I've been ridiculously oblivious about my aim - just accepting any mouse sensitivity that a game threw at me and never realize how my mind behaved to my 3D zone. Every time with every new game I had mouse sensitivity set to game's default and used to try adjusting to it by making minor tweaks. Though it helped me, it was a far cry from developing consistency. Was never critical about my aim until I started getting my buns handed to me in Rainbow Six: Siege which is my first competitive FPS shooter and it is harsh. Now Siege isn't your regular shooter like where you can effortlessly run and gun people. You get only 1 life per round and you need to make it count for your team. Over that, your death can negatively impact the entire round / team plus you need to dynamically strategize how to approach the enemy and site based on your in-game consciousness and situational awareness.

So, here I am. I wish to improve my aim to a point where it becomes my second nature to precisely be able to  click (while control recoil) as soon as I see an enemy's head on the screen. So that I can think about other things in game and to be able to strategize on-the-go to have an edge over the enemy team without worrying / focusing on my aim too much.

I did a bit of research on aiming in general and muscle memory and can definitely vouch for the fact that - One should not expect immediately results while training, muscle memory accumulates overtime just like experience.

I'm just over 20 hours in - so couldn't find anything ground breaking about it. I'm still crap, and it's my fault for ignoring my aim for past 10 years. I'm a casual gamer with a busy work life though. However, with persistent grind and practice, you will definitely see improvement over time. It might take me months or years to accomplish what I wish to but I can certainly tell you that improving your aim will help you have a better experience at FPS games overall not just Siege - be it getting stomped by skilled opponents who are way better than you or you shredding through your opponents like butter.

[b][u]Few tips based on my research: [/u][/b]
1. Though debatable, low sens most of the time is better than high sens in terms of accuracy. So I'd suggest lowering your mouse DPI to your comfort. If currently feel comfortable with your high sensitivity, then step out of our comfort zone and try lower sens for a few days. I'd suggest starting off by 5-6 inches per 360 and work your way down as you practice.

2. Muscle memory is comparatively easier to accumulate on lower sensitivity than using something like 1500 DPI where you're able to do a 360 within 3 inches of surface area on your mouse pad. It takes me 9.67 inches to do a 360 on my mouse pad at 500 DPI. I'm not telling you that you should be able to a quick 360 in-game. [b]Inches per 360 here is just a measure[/b] of how low/high your sens is.

3. Do NOT keep changing your sensitivity drastically just because you had a bad day at a game. If you do so, you'll only hinder your consistency. Think maybe the opponent was better than you? Or maybe your mind is still developing an understanding towards the sensitivity? Just chill, enjoy the game and keep the grind going.

4. Contrary to above, also don't be afraid to make minor tweaks to your sensitivity. You feel comfortable at 8 inches per 360 instead of 8.25? Sure, tweak it. Remember you are learning. However, don't do this too often and think through before making an 8 to something like 7.

5. Try to have the same mouse sensitivity i.e. same inches or cm. per 360 in all the FPS or TPS games you play. Just measure your 360 turn in centimeters from the game you're practicing and apply the same in other games. This is help you build consistency overtime.

[b][u]Few personal tips while playing any game:[/u][/b]

1. Blame yourself when you lose, not others.

2. You need to get better for yourself and to have a better experience while gaming and NOT to flex in front of your friends or to demean your team mates.

3. Be very self-reflective i.e. always criticize yourself not your team mates. Remember, there's always something you could've done better.

4. Your team mate did something wrong or incorrect? Tell them what they should've done and why but not shout at them. But don't try too much to teach them how to play unless they want to learn from you or take your advise. They very well know how to play, it's just their choice on how they want to play.

5. When you ignore your own mistakes and blame it on your team, you will NEVER learn from your own mistakes. You are simply reinforcing your own mind from learning by not accepting things that could've been done better. Never do this.

6. Most importantly, no matter how tense the time is or was, how bad your mind might urge you for the win - always remember, it's just a freaking game. Memories you create while gaming are far more important than screaming / shouting at your friends to win a silly game. Not everyone is equal when it comes to learning anything in life. Help a million times than ranting.

Kovaak's is an amazing aim trainer. It's Ideal for: Overwatch, Quake, CSGO, TF2, Apex Legends and Fortnite. Some others too, probably. To actually benefit you have to do use it right. It's a tool, not a magic steroid that'll instantly make you a god at aiming. If you don't use the tool right, you won't benefit. If you really want to benefit, I recommend reading Aimer7's guide and mostly using the scenarios he recommends. I don't think you have to follow it exactly, but use it as a starting point. Make sure to match your FOV and sensitivity settings with the game you want to get better at. I suggest measuring your sensitivity with a ruler to make sure you don't mismatch it and throw yourself off. I also don't recommend overusing it. If you're spending too much time on it when you could be playing a game for real, it's probably not an efficient use of time. Use it for warming up, training your weak points, or when you just really need to focus on improving your aim.

This game is like your own personnel gym or dojo. You'll be able to isolate and train your aiming.
Flicking, tracking, click-timing, target reading, strafing.. and stuff.

So many scenarios created by it own players/users, a lot of customization, you can even find scenarios where you can find Quake/CSGO/Overwatch settings so you can improve your gunfights and translate it to your actual favorite game.

Using Aimer7 guide (available on his twitch channel page) and practicing daily or sometimes over the week, will improve your aiming habits a lot. Also, if you want to actually learn to aim while MOVING (most scenarios you are a turret, sadly), you can find a couple of good moving scenarios such as 'Pasu Dodge', 'Pasu Track Dodge', 'Air Dodge', 'Anti-Mirror' scenarios, 'lgc3 Reborn'. 'T1 Drop Punish', 'Pistol Strafe Gallery' and more!

It is not for free, but not expensive anyway, so it is 100% worth your money and your time.

This is a no brainer for anyone on M&KB.  I'm still a noob for the most part (1 1/2 yrs total exp), & had no Idea what I was doing when I started gaming (obviously); Fortnite was the game I decided to learn on lmao; looking back I realize that was a little ridiculous.  I already sucked on controller, so I figured I might as well suck on KB&M too & learned to play it since it seemed a more logical choice for FN. That also lets you move on to "mastering" other aspects of whatever game you play; like your footwork, peaking, angles, or building & editing in Fortnite.  So yeah, I've gone on too long; just get it, & git gud!

Not recommended for all games. Ideal for Overwatch, Quake, CSGO, TF2, Apex Legends, maybe Fortnite? Some others too, probably.

To actually benefit you have to do use it right. It's a tool, not a magic steroid that'll instantly make you git gud. If you don't use the tool right, you won't benefit.

I recommend reading Aimer7's guide and mostly using the scenarios he recommends. I don't think you have to follow it exactly, but use it as a starting point. Make sure to match your FOV and sensitivity settings with the game you want to get better at. I suggest measuring your sensitivity with a ruler to make sure you don't mismatch it and throw yourself off.

I also don't recommend overusing it. If you're spending too much time on it when you could be playing a game for real, it's probably not an efficient use of time. Use it for warming up, training your weak points, or when you just really need to focus on improving your aim.

After an update to the Unreal engine, you can no longer have any sound effects on certain AMD/Realtek hardware. It's a known problem with UE4, and even though a suggested fix was made to the dev (after being implemented on other games with the exact same problem) they don't acknowledge it or make any such fix. So unless you turn off all audio the game constantly stutters whenever sounds play.

Extremely ridiculous considering the fix is to turn off an equalizer effect on the developer's side.
developer_response: This is actually the first time I'm hearing about this issue.  I'll look into it, so thanks for the heads-up.  I'm not sure where you attempted to contact me in the past, but for future reference the best ways I'm fairly response on the email listed in the game store page, or the game's Discord server, or reddit DM.

I thought I had decent aim but i felt it was lacking at times so I decided to try kovaak's. At first I was disappointed at how simple the top rated games were and I was skeptical that it would translate into other games. On top of that the challenges felt very taxing on my brain and I would get burnt out after 20 minutes. The median scores were surprisingly high and seemed out of reach. However I kept playing for 20 minutes a day during my down time and within a week the challenges were no longer exhausting me mentally and became very fun. I found myself playing kovaak's over my other fps games, trying to top my high scores and climb the leaderboards became very addictive, especially coupled with the fact that I knew I was becoming a better gamer in the process. Now after just  3 weeks of playing I consistantly score in the top 80-90%. I've noticed a huge impact in other fps games; I get compliments on my aim from spectating teamates regularly now. This is coming from someone who had good aim before they used Kovaaks Aim Trainer. For starters, don't think using an aim trainer will automatically make you a god at the games you play. Refining aim is like taking the frame of a car, getting the best parts, washing it, and polishing it. Then using it to rule over the people who didn't do what you did, and it allows you to keep up with the people who have also got the best parts, washed it, and polished it. But the people who refined there engines will always dominate the people who refined there frames. What I'm really trying to get at here is game sense and decision making dominate good aim. You can have an aimbot but get dominated by a pro with a ball mouse, without the right knowledge of the game. Kovaaks Aim Trainer worked really well for me. I started in the 4 digit area of the leaderboards an in about 13 hours of gameplay made it to top 100. I use it to prep for a gaming session as it gives me the best ability I can have aim wise. It has also brought me to a point where I feel like I'm improving in my aim at a really fast pace. Kovaaks Aim Trainer hit right in the spots I needed. Now taking the information I gave you here I hope you can see if this this game is right for you.

I've always been pretty good at first person shooters. First BR was pubg, was extremely inconsistent and was only good with teamwork/strategic play. Was tired of getting fucked up in pubg and moved to fortnite. Got pretty damn good at fortnite but was still inconsistent with aiming, and i carried myself through the game by just being a great builder. Was so tired of both pubg and fortnite that i was just about done with gaming in general for a bit till the gaming industry shaped up. Apex legends released and i was hooked instantly. As my love for the game grew, so did my desire to be a competent, skilled shooter. I started browsing for aim trainers,  and found kovaaks and bought it. Barely used it for a few weeks, and even tried to refund it... Glad i didn't.


At first i started off by doing random scenarios that looked fun. Eventually noticed that i wasn't making progress so i looked up a guide and found aimer 7's. Started at the very beginning to build a great foundation, did a whole sensitivity/dpi overhaul and it's all been uphill from that point. I've grown to be extremely competent and very consistent and i constantly improve. My best advice it to dedicate ATLEAST 30 minutes to kovaaks a day. Always take 1-2 day break every other week or some. This will let you improve much faster. I dedicate anywhere from 30minutes to 1 1/2 hours of my time to kovaaks every day.


Is it worth $10? Fuck yes it is. Don't buy it if you want a quick fix to your shitty aim. Your improvement is based on how persistent you are with it. I didn't start kovaaks just to be a tryhard. I started kovaaks to have more fun in games. The better i am, the more happy i am in games. 

I'd like to thank kovaaks for helping me have an enhanced gaming experience, and for allowing me to meet awesome people that comes along with being decent at any given game. Have a good one folks!

As I write this review, KovaaK's FPS Aim Trainer is my favorite of its kind. Its a bare-bones, ultra-customizable program that is fully capable of providing a workout for your FPS (and even your TPS) niche. Yes, it comes with a price tag, but for those looking to get the most of out a training program I recommend the investment. It should go without saying that KovaaK's (or any aim trainer for that matter) is not a magic formula for improving your FPS game. You'll need to apply yourself and commit. You may also need to do a little research on good mouse/recommended DPI settings, in conjunction with a training routine that is right for your current skill level. And as always, KovaaK's can greatly improve your reflexes and hand-eye coordination, but gamesense is something best learned on the field. Highly recommended.

This game is wonderful. I bought it after my friend started playing it, and right off the bat i loved it. I saw improvements in my aim immediately. The sens converter alone makes this game worth buying (off the context that you know its an aim trainer). The maps though which is the other 50% of this game, just makes Kovaaks 50% more amazing. The staple maps are GREAT like Ascended training v3/Pressure aiming 7 targets/and all the title frenzy's to state a few. With the hundreds and hundreds of other maps been and being created open up so many opportunities and possibility's. The game runs very smoothly and its so simple, but hits the aim trainer holy grail design philosophy nail straight on the head.

I do have slight criticisms though. I bought this game specifically for training my aim in Rainbow six, and here is where one of the only bugs/lack of features I've encountered. If you are in full screen and you tab out, it doesn't minimize the window. Another thing is that if you have a second game open for whatever reason like you are waiting for a queue to pop, the mouse wont be anchored to the center of the screen once you start a map. That means if you move your mouse and start to shoot, you WILL click off the screen over and over again, because you move your mouse a lot during this game of course lol (which is another dumb thing about full screen in this game, it doesn't keep your mouse inside your main monitor). The last thing is how you change mouse sens for specific guns per each map. In each specific map It gives you a lot more control for gun sens, like zoom sens and FOV. The problem though is that its way too annoying, there are so many random guns in some maps for some reason that don't even have settings for sens, and some that do have sens options but don't do anything if you do change them. I ask if kovaak would just force map devs to put the main gun with the ACTUAL sens options in a new tab he would patch into the game that only has sens settings for that map and nothing else. (so custom cross hairs and whatever else can stay in its original tab)

How i would rate this game outta 50 is 49/50. it completes its task better than every other game for aim training, it has intuitive mechanics, easy to understand useful maps, and a really extensive range of map pools with an amazing sens converter, with nominal annoyances altogether. I would recommend this to any fps player who wants to improve their aim

Come into this game, spending only a couple hours in it and really quickly my rust came off and literally with in a couple days I've gone up two ranks (albeit gold nova, so not actually impressive), but keep in mind this is after like a year or two of being the same rank when I would casual play.

It's nice to get closer to my old skill level and it's really satisfying to play well (even got called a smurf :D). 

==Sort of negatives

If you're looking for a game, there isn't one, at least from what I've seen so far. The game to me is the challenge you set for yourself, trying to break your own PR. I mean that should be obvious, but just in case you were thinking there was an actual game behind this. You would be mistaken.

The UI is ugly as heck and can be a little wonky at times. 

For some reason I have to click play for the challenge to start, but it just starts instantly. Would be fantastic if there was a count down before the challenge started. 

Overall, 100% worth it so far. It's actually been fun grinding and trying to beat my numbers and hearing the little ding sounds.

I typically play Overwatch, as far as FPS games go.
I'm also somewhat new to Mouse and keyboard shooting (I play on consoles a lot) and my aim was passable at a general level. 

I bought this 2 days ago ($10) and it was instantly worth the price.
After 1 day of using it with my Overwatch settings I warmed up on it, immediately went into OW and played some hitscan (Ashe, if you're curious).  My average accuracy had gone up by 8-10% 

I thought it might be a fluke, but I tried it over the course of around 15 games.  My average was consistently up, give or take 2 bad games where we were just getting shut down and I didn't have the space to aim as comfortably as I'd have liked.

8-10% isn't huge, but that's a lot more shots and critical hits that I'm landing compared to prior games.  I'm tracking a bit better, I'm managing to focus on individual targets and better remove the enemy supports if they're visible and there's a gap to hit them.  I'm not amazing (I'm mostly a tank player) but I think this could definitely make my DPS role more serviceable with time.  I will ALWAYS warm up on this before I boot up the game from now on.

developer_response:
Heya!  Sorry about the inconvenience.  There is a bug that affects less than 1% of users where the game chooses the wrong monitor every time it starts up.  Unfortunately the engine isn't exposing which monitor to select to me, so I can't even make it an option without digging into a lot of things right now.  But there is a workaround.

When you are in game (and not in menus), press alt+enter, then use windows key+arrow (left or right) twice, then alt+enter again.  It should move to the correct monitor and be full-screened.  Sorry for the inconvenience.

Also, I see you are probably outside of Steam's refund window based on time played.  If you are still having troubles and want a refund for the game, I'd be happy to paypal you the money.  HMU on Steam if you want to talk about that (I sent a friend req).

Easily the best aim trainer on Steam. This actually helps training 3D aim unlike the many other aim trainers which are either restricted to 2D aim or flick training. If you want to hone your tracking skills this trainer is definitely for you. There are less options for flick practice, but a free trainer like Aimtastic is already sufficient for that. 

The customisability (both in terms of UI/graphics/input and in terms of practice scenarios) is fantastic. No matter which game you're playing you can easily replicate it in this aim trainer. The wide selection of scenarios from the Workshop makes it even more comfortable. 

On the technical side of things it's pretty much flawless as well. FPS cap can be set high enough, input lag is low (although a cl_input_subframe setting like in Reflex would be nice) and the most important yaw values for sensitivity multiplication are present as well. The only thing missing would be a full integration of Povohat's accel driver, but you can use just that of course. 

In short: Don't waste money on Aim Hero or similar stuff and get this aim trainer instead, it's definitely worth it.

Would I recommend this game?
Yes.

Do I think this game is a reasonable price?
Yes.

Has the game got any technical issues or bugs?
No bugs as far as I can tell. There seems to be the occasional frame drop when a bot spawns, this could be due to my PC as it drops like this in other games too.

Has this game helped me with my aim?
Yes, only a short time on this game really improved my muscle memory for tracking. 

Does this game contain the features promised?
Yes, I can manipulate the bots and there are many preset modes for different styles of aiming such as tracking, flicking and predicting enemy movement. 

Really happy I bought this. Extremely challenging modes that are sure to help me on this
